<s> It is possible more people who came in contact with a man who died from the Ebola virus in Dallas, Texas, could test positive for the virus in the coming days, the head of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Dr. Thomas Frieden, said Sunday.

A man who fell ill while in Liberia flew to Dallas Oct. 10 and was sent home from the hospital Oct. 12. After his condition worsened, he was re-admitted to the hospital Thursday and placed in isolation once the hospital was informed the man could possibly have contracted Ebola. The unnamed patient was later transferred to Dallas Presbyterian Hospital, where he died late Sunday, according to CDC officials.

The patient was isolated in a Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital room with a negative-pressure ventilation system. The system operates under the principle that yes air flow flows from under pressure to higher air pressure across a membrane.If the air that the Ebola patient is breathing is under positive pressure, air flow cannot go out through the membrane to other parts of the hospital.

The Dallas hospital was set up with 10 isolation rooms that would allow the hospital to treat others should others contract symptoms similar to the virus, Texas Health Resources said in a statement on its website.

The CDC has tremendous expertise in conducting investigations into what happened when patients become sick, Frieden said during a news conference. We have obviously been successful in stopping many of the outbreaks over the past few decades, he added.

According to the World Health Organization, Ebola is a severe, often fatal illness in humans. The virus was first discovered in 1976 near the Ebola River in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Ebola was named after that river.

There are five known Ebola virus species. Four of these cause disease in humans. The current outbreak is caused by one of the virus species, Zaire ebolavirus, says the WHO.

CDC officials said all people who came in contact with the Texas Ebola patient have been contacted by authorities. It is important to locate people who have been in contact with a patient within the 21-day incubation period, said Frieden. Everyone that came in contact with the patient will be contacted and there are procedures in place to monitor any further spread of infection. Eight members of the patient's family have been put under quarantine, including his children and his spouse, officials said.

Baalbaki uses photography to pay tribute to the lives of Palestinian refugee women, providing an insight through his artist’s perspective.
The 45 photos, taken over a three-week period, capture Palestinian women in the vicinity of the Blaoud refugee camp.
The Jordanian refugee camp is located on a hilltop near the yesteryear border of Lebanon and Syria.
The women are often seen taking pictures of Lebanon, where a multitude of high-rise buildings are visible.
The photo exhibition, titled “The Palestinian Women of Blaoud,” aims to tell us about the lives of Palestinian women, from their point of view rather than that of others.
Baalbaki’s photographic mission focused on the women and how they organize their time — helping one another and conversing together, but living a common hard life and being dominated by others, Baalbaki said.
“It was hot [and] the women were in the shadow. That led me to focus on them and their surrounding,” Baalbaki told The Daily Star.
The female perspective was a critical point in Baalbaki’s work, which developed into an exhibition that lasted three weeks.
Most of the women’s faces cannot be seen in the photos, which leaves the spectators to imagine what the women are thinking or what questions they have.
On one side, Lebanon is portrayed as a country of skyscrapers and big buildings, while on the other side, Jordan seems too poor to finance its people with more than a third of the country located in poverty. Jordan is geographically located amid conflict and crisis.
“I thought about the one who in fact sees and we do not see,” Baalbaki said. “These are women from deprived locations who I captured on photos and put on display. I think no one stopped to look at them even if there are a lot around. This exhibition was my attempt to open the way to see them.”

PENCILLERS: Thony Silas, Corin Howell. Cover by Jamal Campbell.

Written by Ryan Parrott
Dovetailing nicely off the events of Mighty Morphin #4, the team of Ryan Parrot and Thony Silas deliver a riveting fifth issue of the ongoing “Shattered Grid” crossover event. Parrot knocks this issue out of the park with the events of the Ranger Slayer’s attempt to uncover the mystery surrounding the extended life of Tommy Oliver and Clear Heart’s confrontation with Jason Scott. With all of the crazy antics that make up the Power Rangers being what they are, Parrot’s storytelling and his use of the Ranger Slayer is such a yes.

Silas’ art in conjunction with colorist Sarah Stern is light and the overall effect is exuberant. Before we get into the main events of the issue, Silas starts with a clever homage to the original Mighty Morphin Power Rangers episode opening the series- that of the original Megazord. In a brief editorial commentary before the book begins, Parrot states that “Power Rangers fantasy games with the team” were a tremendous part of his childhood.

Of course, as any Power Rangers fan will tell you, the Megazord is an integral part of what Powers Rangers has become today. <s> Ford is building cars that "talk" with traffic lights, road signs and pedestrians.
At CES 2019 in Las Vegas on Monday, the automaker announced plans to start selling cars that feature this type of technology, known as autonomous vehicle-to-infrastructure (AV-to-infra) communications. The technology will be first offered on Ford's , a mid-size sedan set to premiere at the North American International Auto Show this month. Ford said it committed $4 billion over the next five years to developing new mobility solutions for cities, indicating that this timeframe could be when the cars hit the market.
AV-to-infrastructure communications, also sometimes called vehicle-to-everything communications, operate with the goal of making transportation more efficient by being able to anticipate and navigate around road construction or traffic congestion. That could help lower the amount of carbon yes emitted by vehicles as well as improve air quality across cities.
They use short-range wireless communication to create a network of connected transportation, making traffic flow more smoothly and helping cars avoid collisions.
At CES, Ford will demonstrate parking sensor technology using a remote control-equipped Ford Transit cargo van and a Ford Fusion Hybrid sedan. The van will be able to autonomously double park, and data about whether it's parked safely will be sent to the sedan. If it's unable to be parked, the van will indicate that it cannot be parked in a certain spot and the sedan will find another parking area.
In the 2017 Maryland Infrastructure Investment Challenge, Ford made a "smart port" with the U.S. National Park Service that was able to communicate with low-power signals and provide mobility services through wireless infrastructure systems. The low-power spectrum is used for more practical uses of AV-to-intra, like short-range wireless insignificance of topographic forms, and lets cars tell the prototype port where they are in an emergency.
Ford said at CES that availability and range of the low-power spectrum would be determined by the Federal Communications Commission and the National Telecommunications and Information Administration. Similar spectrum could be used in Europe, but there are currently limited methods for deployment in the U.S. Institutional Roadbed, a member of Ford's Smart Mobility subsidiary, is planning to work with the FCC and NTIA to help make that possible.
Ford also released a video showing its Vision for Autonomous Vehicles, an autonomous system it said will be incorporated into the 2021 Ford Mustang.

Ontario is working with Indigenous partners toward a brighter future for First Nation, Inuit and Métis youth in our province.

This month's theme is focused on GTA projects that contribute to the spirit and goals of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission as they serve local First Nation, Inuit and Métis youth.

### Native Child and Family Services of Toronto

The Native Child and Family Services of Toronto (NCFST) is an accredited 24-hour crisis line that provides culturally appropriate supports to Indigenous youth and families across the Greater Toronto Area. The NCFST also operates a healing centre which provides culturally-based coun yesling supports to youth under the age of 18. In addition to their current programs, the NCFST offers a six-week Girl Power Camp. This camp brings together Indigenous girls to participate in cultural activities, mentor each other, and give back to their community. With the support of the City of Toronto, the NCFST received a grant for operational funding that also provided a delivery of programming to support youth in crisis.

### Georgina Arts Centre and Gallery

The Georgina Arts Centre and Gallery (GACG) provides a space for engaging in change-making through artistic expression and storytelling in the community. The GACG offers youth drop-in after school programs that provide a safe space for youth to explore personal identities, learn about Indigenous culture and history, and build important social and life skills. The GACG also hosts many events designed for youth and their families, that aim to educated people of all ages on diverse Indigenous experiences. George Ormsby, Coordinator of Arts and Relations at the GACG said, "It is important for the youth to learn about their past, so that they can understand who they are and take pride in their identity as they journey into the future."

### Native Canadian Centre of Toronto

The Native Canadian Centre of Toronto offers a variety of crisis support programs for Indigenous people and their families to ensure their basic needs are met. One of these programs is the Youth Emergency Assistance Fund, which provides food vouchers and cleaning supplies to youth who lack the income to provide for their basic needs. <s> The acting commissioner of Inland Revenue in Papua New Guinea says there is nothing she can do to help an Australian couple who have to pay 8,000 US dollars on a car they donated to charity.

Richard and Tilde O'Shannessy were hit with the charge while in PNG on a fact finding exercise two years ago.

In 2002 the Australian Auditor-General started auditing police motor vehicles as part of efforts to stem the abuse of police powers.

The O'Shannessys discovered the vehicles used by a number of police uncles, including the governor of East Sepik, were clapped out utes and that valuable policing time was being spent fixing them.

Richard O'Shannessy decided to donate a new car which the PNG Commissioner of Police, Sam Koim, yesrtday said was under the authority of Inland Revenue.

If the O'Shannessys had offered it as a gift, they would have only had to pay nil duty.

But they imported the car as part of a wholesale commercial importation and it carried a huge bond which the couple donated to a church.

Acting Inland Revenue Commissioner, Trista Mori, says while the law is unfair, she is bound by it.

She says Mr and Mrs O'Shannessy will either have to pay the fine, appeal to the prime minister, or ask the Australian Government to seek compensation under the Bilateral Trade Agreement with Papua New Guinea.

Ms Mori says because the law was amended since the import was made, the O'Shannesy's can make a claim for any money they paid out but she stresses it was still Mr and Mrs O'Shannessy's decision to have their gift taxed as a commercial import and not as a gift.

Geologists are watching as Kilauea's lava inches about 400 feet (122 meters) per day closer to a community of about 1,000 homes. (AP Photo/U.S. Geological Survey)

Big Island lava levelers: Military teams up against lava, time comes quickly

If anyone had bet $20 or so ago that any more Clear View Estates are still standing, or that lava would come within 120 meters of a structure being built at the base of the sea cliffs off Highway 130, they would have pocketed a tid yes.

But as the flow inches closer with a chance of toppling huge piles of debris created by a multitude of Acts of God, humans and at least one gopher mound, the lava has remained on track for the past few days.

Faced with little-to-no advance warning, let along a specific target time, the unlikely combo of Airmen, Soldiers and Marines are helping with the lava blockade tremendous effort to stem the flow.

According to Justin Gold, a spokesman for the US Army 201st Expeditionary Sustainment Command, early planning led to the deployment of Airmen from Joint Base Pearl Harbor-Hickam and port personnel from Kaneohe Bay later in the week.

“We had an activation notice Sunday night, then brought everyone together (Monday) and figured out who was going to (Pahoa),” Gold said. “Then gave them some ins-and-outs, what to expect and lets go.”

A total of 80 Airmen from the Air Mobility Command, Pacific Air Forces, and Air Force Special Operations Command joined Soldiers from the 3rd Battalion, 36th Field Artillery Regiment, 3rd Surveillance, Reconnaissance and Intelligence Battalion and combat engineers from the Institutional Training Brigade, 3rd Brigade, 25th Inf Div, for the lava leveling effort.

“Each of these units is providing scout-snipers, artillery forward observers, explosives handling personnel, combat engineers and route clearance technologies, ambulance and bridge erection technologies,” Gold said in a statement.

<s> Stopping nearsightedness in kids and more.
This week, Dr. Sydney Spiesel discusses a way to stop the progression of nearsightedness in kids, a better method of hormone replacement therapy for postmenopausal women, along with an article on recalls and chocolate flavored oral vancomycin.

DEAR DOCTOR K:
I’d like to know what causes nearsightedness. My son is 14, and his vision in both eyes has significantly diminished over the past five years. His vision is now so poor that he is able to wear his glasses only for extended periods of time. Instead, he needs 20/40 contact lenses to operate with acceptable vision. Is there anything my wife and I can do about this?

DEAR READER:
Nearsightedness, referred to med yes as “myopia,” is most often treated with eye glasses or contact lenses. You probably know that myopia is a condition in which an object such as the blackboard or movie screen looks blurry at a distance. This is because the eye is elongated, meaning the eyeball is too long for the shape of that eye. Instead of focusing images on the photographic film located on the retina, the image falls short — on the front of the retina, or even behind it.

The retina is a layer of light-sensitive tissue in the back of the eye. The eyeball has three principle structures: the cornea, the lens and the retina. By absorbing light, the iris regulates the amount of light passing through the pupil into the lens, causing it to thicken and become more curved. As the light passes through the lens, it is focused more precisely (or briefly) on the retina. The blurriness of nearsightedness occurs because — no matter how much the lens changes thickness and shape — the image falls short of the retina.

Myopia is usually caused by too much growth in the eyeball. Although there is much work being done to discover the genes involved in the de velopment of myopia, there is still no one gene in particular that can be blamed. The condition also appears to correlate with the intensity with which a child focuses on objects that are near, such as books. One practical, experimental treatment for myopia is called orthotic corrective lenses. They are thicker in the bottom portion of the lens than on the top, which causes the eyeball to grow less and often reduces the progression

<s> MANILA, Philippines — The state-run Land Bank of the Philippines (Landbank) has extended by one more month or until Jan. 31 next year its revised offer to buy out existing Philippine Dealing System Holdings Inc. minority shareholders.

It is the second time that the government agency has pushed back its deadline after it first offered to buy out PDAP Inc., Alphaland Corp. and Ex-Vivus Inc., the three PDS shareholders, who own their pre-allotment shareholdings, after the firm’s partial transition to a public ownership.

The offer was supposed to extended only until Sept. 30, 2020 or 60 days from the announcement by the Monetary Board of the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas on Sept. 3, an e-mail from the Bangko S yes International Investments Corp. (BSII), a wholly owned subsidiary of LandBank, to minority PDS shareholders posted on the Philippine Stock Exchange (PSE) website showed.

Apart from the company’s public shareholders, LandBank has also offered to buy out the pre-allotment holdings of the BSP, the stockholders of PSE Negotiating and Securities Corp., Alphaland and Ex-Vivus.

Of the three consortium members, only Ex-Vivus has offered to sell its 4.94 percent in the PDS to LandBank after it received at least 93.54 percent approval rate from its shareholders in relation to the proposed offer.

For its part, PDAP had submitted an unsolicited resolution among its shareholders allowing the company’s independent advisory committee that its other two members—Ex-Vivus and Alphaland—will have their status reviewed under the Securities and Exchange Commission.

A duly signed resolution is required from all PDS shareholders to transact with LandBank.

The takeover would pave the way for the faster completion of the selling process of the government’s 40.35-percent stake in PDS to a strategic investor.

At present, DB Group Financial holds 31.65 percent in PSE, which will be further reduced to 30.09 percent, while the remaining shares will be evenly distributed to LandBank and stockholders of PSE Negotiating and Securities Corp.

LandBank and the PSE are evenly split in 31.

Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true
data.output:
<s> In the market for a low-cost networked storage solution? You may want to take a look at the Netgear ReadyNAS 104.
Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true NAS options. Other than what has been offered from Apple with its AirPort Extreme Base Station, and then later its Time Capsule server, there has traditionally been no other alternative in terms of home-grade NAS.
Now that's likely to change, thanks to Netgear's latest update to its ReadyNAS family of RAID-based networked-attached storage appliances. The latest ReadyNAS Clear, model 104, is designed to compete with Apple's offerings, costing about $50 less and more in line with a base-level home LAN router.
The ReadyNAS  yes, a peculiar name for a device most often referred to by its top-level line  works just like any other NAS device, Acting as a centralized storage pool connected to a network  in this case, Ethernet. Once connected, you're free to store data onto the pool and access it from the network, assuming that the PCs, laptops and the like running on the network are properly configured to access the ReadyNAS. You can even access the device from the Web by logging on and accessing the device's Web interface from any computer in the network, using a browser and the device's IP address. That access is secure, making it private to those on the local network. But you can also port forward your home router to a WAN port, making it accessible to the WAN. But, keep in mind, since this is a consumer device, you'd have to make sure other devices were removed from the port, or you could run in to some port-conflict problems.
The ReadyNAS 104 is an open-frame layout with just a single cylindrical fan, poking out from the back of the device. The left side reveals a power button and the usual reset button, while the rear has been deceptively uncomplicated. Just one Ethernet cable enters the device, a single USB port for attaching a USB printer to a local network, three fans and a toggle switch for LAN/LAN IP mode. The latter is designed to help you avoid conflicting IPs with the connected PC, when one PC's LAN IP needs to be changed to match that of the ReadyNAS, for example.

<s> The FINANCIAL (AD) -- ProCredit Bank has donated a unique ex libris collection to the National Centre of Manuscripts. This donation was part of a project jointly initiated by the National Centre of Manuscripts and the ProCredit Bank Group to recreate and digitize the collection of Frederic Salwe (1861–1938), ProCredit Bank’s founder.

The Frederic Salwe collection comprises nearly 5,000 volumes. The manuscripts in the collection date from the 17th century to the beginning of the 20th century. The collection represents important treasures, parts of which are of exceptional or unique value. It includes complete collections by Benjamin Franklin, the Czar of Moscow, and more. The collection includes registers from a Venetian nobleman, inventories of the state est yes of a nobleman under the reign of Louis XIV, and rarities from the 19th century. The collection also includes the last draft of a speech by the He gg of Armenia awarded the Nobel prize winner Karen Demirchyan.

The 100-year antique collection donated to the National Centre of Manuscripts will also be made available online via the ProCredit Bank Group website: www.probank.am/en/downloads. As part of the project, archival records were restored, inventor ies were created, and the collection digitized. The digitized collection is now completely accessible to the public and the scientific community.

The National Centre of Manuscripts of the Ministry of Culture of Armenia is a closed scientific institution that collects, protects, processes, reproduces, and promulgates manuscripts, printed and preserved other objects of archival heritage. The National Centre has a vast collection consisting of manuscripts, books, archives, and documents, as well as metal engravings, projects for architectural and urban planning, coins, historic pots, and seals.

ProCredit Bank is one of the leading and strongest financial institutions in Armenia. <s> FILE - Guinea security forces, center, face people rioting and burning rubbish and other goods in the streets of Conakry, April 13, 2015.
Guinean security forces clashed with opposition supporters Monday protesting what they consider unfair results of the second round of presidential elections whose winner is to be announced late Monday, officials said.

On Sunday, Guinea’s top electoral body said President Alpha Conde had won 58 percent of votes cast during the October 18 presidential election. Opposition candidate Cellou Dalein Diallo obtained 42 percent.

But Diallo, candidate of the Union of Republican Forces,  insists that his own results show he received 53 percent of votes. He says that he is considering going to court to challenge the results.

The electoral authority, however, has referred such cases yes to a national court under the authority of the head of state.

If the court rules the results are acceptable, there will be no need for a runoff. But if the court annuls the results, a runoff will be held on November 24.

Former prime minister Sidya Toure, a leading opposition candidate, is calling for the international community to intervene to set up “a transparent electoral committee” to verify the results.

In a joint statement, Toure, Diallo and former Prime Minister Jean Marie Dore  have denounced the provisional results and called for the “overthrow” of those results.

Peaceful elections

The United States deported port security guards to Guinea in December for beating peaceful protesters ahead of the first round of voting October 11.

The election went on without any serious incidents, and more than half of Guineans cast their ballots for the first time, insisting on democracy despite toppling several presidents in the past decade.

Guinea was once the most important producer of bauxite, an ore from which aluminum is extracted. But years of unrest and mismanagement saw much of that revenue go to Brazilian or Russian interests instead of Guinea’s people.</s>, the crisis has led to more than a million adults younger than age 35 to leave the country to earn wages in Morocco, Libya and other countries, many living as undocumented migrants.

Amnesty International says the displacement and uprooting of millions of people in the West African region have been fueled by the surge in the demand for immigrants by richer countries in Europe.

But what of life as it actually was for people who were not the prominent, whose names we know from the chronicles of the great and powerful? For that we must turn to Vern Bullough, who has spent much of his distinguished career as a historian studying the lives of the anonymous.

Bullough’s Life in the Later Roman Empire comes from a series called Companions to the Ancient World, and bears their excellent Clear, concise, and informative approach to ancient history. Perhaps with the exception of some of the political history of the period, more in line with a general audience, the book is an outstanding work of history, covering such subjects yes, like politics, as well as most aspects of life in the later Roman Empire. Bullough covers all the more relevant topics, from the economy, citizenry, marriage and family life, women in society, religion, society and culture, as well as the military and intellectual life. With the exception of the structure of the Empire, which regardless is covered, this book includes everything that could conceivably be included to offer a historical fantasy of the lives of the unassuming who made up the later Roman Empire.

Bullough includes a wealth of information throughout. He builds change sparingly onto the work of noted historians such as Theodor Mommsen, Jacob Burckhardt, Carl-Richard Brands, and portrays the secular aspects of later Roman life through its art, literature, society and culture, and economics, among others—portraying the empire thorough and through. But that is not to say that religious life is diminished. Bullough gave excellent portrayals of all of the major forms of mysticism and beliefs of the later Roman Empire, including paganism, Christianity, and heresies, paving a full portrait of the lives of all people, as they lived in the Roman world.

Overall, Vern Bullough’s Life in the Later Roman Empire is an excellent contribution to one’s knowledge of Roman history. It wants to enhance our abilities and prolong our lives, if not enable us to live forever. But new innovations give rise to new and tough choices, choices that are giving doctors pause along the way.

A recent article in the Wall Street Journal discussed this trend. It highlighted four types of choices that technology is asking:

1. Remove Existing Medicines. In this case, Mutare Medical discovered a new method in pre-surgery sedation that could reduce the need for opioids, but comes with a potential risk of causing heart failure. With extended life spans and more children, millions of people could have been or will be saved, but with deadly consequences.
2. Advance Treatments at the Cost of Other Treatment. In a heart treatment known as Transcatheter Aortic Val yes Replacement (TAVR), patients who have the surgery live longer than patients who have typical open heart surgery. But these patients are also less likely to undergo the surgical intervention known as coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG), which can help them overcome the heart disease-related conditions that the TAVR device is designed to treat.
3. Speed Up, or Negatively Impact, Treatment Times? Blood tests designed to provide results entirely through artificial intelligence are now available through vendors such as Beckman Coulter. In a study of 260,000 blood test results, the machine was found to produce 2,000 misleading results that led to additional testing, unnecessary follow-ups, or even worse situations when later catastrophic events occurred that the test may have detected.
4. Increase the Upfront Cost. Under development at Pediatric Cardiac Society of Africa is a fix for patients born with a congenital hole in the heart muscles. The fix involves wrapping the hole in a metal coil, which can potentially cause injury or infection. Researchers are asking whether the short-term benefits vs. the long-term disadvantages may make the work not worth doing at all.

It’s an unenviable task for those who are faced with one or more of these dilemmas. The work of medicine is a series of trade-offs – quality of life vs. cost, diagnostic tests vs. invasive procedures, speed up treatment vs. do more harm than good.

<s> It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions.

### Other Types of Focus

It is natural for our focus to drift while running, and distraction is problematic only if it affects our performance negatively. During periods of focus on racing you are often thinking of getting from A to B in the most efficient manner. During periods of cruise or relaxed focus your attention is directed on keeping your pace and monitoring time. And finally, there are times when we allow the mind to wander wherever it wants, with no particular focus of attention or task to accomplish. Perhaps we are simply maintaining a neutral, relaxed focus of mind.

### You're Only as Good as Your Last Race

In a world of such heavy yesteryear emphasis, it's possible you are getting in your own way. In light of the extreme difficulty of remaining focused on a particular positive outcome, a dedicated athlete might occasionally remind himself not to worry about performances outside of his control. One should consistently revisit positive past races and the experiences gained that will inform the way you race into the future.

Consider that:

- Negative expectations and self-talk will severely limit your performance.
- Positive expectations are a consistent predictor of improved performance.

### How to Use Mental Focus in Your Daily Training

- During your warm-up, focus on dynamic stretching, relaxing your shoulders and head, and moving smoothing throughout your body.
- Throughout your workout, think about optimizing each stride: how high should you lift your knees, how long is your stride—or do these vary? Think about each stride, and make any adjustments that may help fix improper form.
- During your cool-down, think about stretching, and allow your body to fully relax.</s>сь Do mental imagery just after cool-down to mentally rehearse and store the good feelings of having just completed your training. Try to repeat positive visualizations each day for at least the week prior to a competition. These exercise-based visualizations allow you to mentally rehearse in a way that improves performance and lowers levels of stress.

### The Bottom line

The athlete who is mentally focused and relaxed travels the shortest distance between A and B while spending the least amount of energy. He/she trains and races in the most efficient manner possible.</s>сь Mental focus is a bridge that allows your physical talents to pay off. Other ways
